SSH config, and the agent.

Two things make SSH genuinely pleasant to live with day to day: a config file full of aliases, and an agent that remembers your unlocked key.

Start with the config file, tilde-slash-dot-ssh-slash-config. Typing out ssh dash-i some-key dash-p some-port user-at-really-long-hostname gets old fast. So in the config file you define a Host block. You write Host, then a short alias like "work," and underneath it, indented, you set HostName to the real address, User to your username, and IdentityFile to the key to use. Now you just type ssh work, and it fills in all of that. You can also set ProxyJump on a host, so that ssh internal-db1 automatically tunnels through a bastion server first. The rules are: each Host block matches by pattern, and wildcards are allowed; the first match for each setting wins, so order matters; and a Host-star block at the end sets defaults for everything. The core keys to know are HostName, User, Port, IdentityFile, and ProxyJump for bastions.

Now the agent. A passphrase-protected key is more secure, but it'd be annoying to type the passphrase on every single connection. So ssh-agent holds your decrypted keys in memory, and you enter the passphrase just once per session. You add a key to the agent with ssh-add, which grabs your default key, or ssh-add and a specific path. And ssh-add dash-l lists the keys the agent is currently holding. On most desktop systems the agent starts automatically at login.

Finally, agent forwarding. Say you SSH into a bastion, and from there you need to SSH onward to an internal server. Agent forwarding, turned on with ssh dash-capital-A, or ForwardAgent yes in the config, lets the bastion use your local agent to authenticate that next hop. The key itself never leaves your laptop; the bastion just gets to ask your agent to sign challenges. But, and this is the security caveat, while you're connected, that intermediate host can use your key. So never enable agent forwarding to a server you don't fully trust. In most cases ProxyJump is the safer choice anyway, because it tunnels your connection straight through the bastion without ever giving the bastion access to your agent.
